==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shackle
<hw>Shac"kle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Stubble.</def>
<mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Pegge.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shackle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Shackle
<hw>Shac"kle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Generally used in the
plural.]</ety> <ety>[OE. <ets>schakkyll</ets>, <ets>schakle</ets>, AS.
<ets>scacul</ets>, <ets>sceacul</ets>, a shackle, fr. <ets>scacan</ets>
to shake; cf. D. <ets>schakel</ets> a link of a chain, a mesh, Icel.
<ets>sk⟦oum⟧kull</ets> the pole of a cart. See <er>Shake</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Something which confines the legs or arms so as to
prevent their free motion; specifically, a ring or band inclosing the
ankle or wrist, and fastened to a similar shackle on the other leg or
arm, or to something else, by a chain or a strap; a gyve; a
fetter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His <qex>shackles</qex> empty left; himself escaped clean.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, that which checks or prevents free
action.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His very will seems to be in bonds and <qex>shackles</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A fetterlike band worn as an ornament.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Most of the men and women . . . had all earrings made of gold, and
gold <qex>shackles</qex> about their legs and arms.</q>
<rj><qau>Dampier.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A link or loop, as in a chain, fitted with a movable
bolt, so that the parts can be separated, or the loop removed; a
clevis.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A link for connecting railroad cars; -- called also
<altname>drawlink</altname>, <altname>draglink</altname>, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>The hinged and curved bar of a padlock, by which it
is hung to the staple.</def> <rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Shackle joint</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>a joint
formed by a bony ring passing through a hole in a bone, as at the bases
of spines in some fishes.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1321 --></p>

<p><ent>Shackle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Shackle
<hw>Shac"kle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Shackled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Shackling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To tie or
confine the limbs of, so as to prevent free motion; to bind with
shackles; to fetter; to chain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To lead him <qex>shackled</qex>, and exposed to scorn⟦br⟧
Of gathering crowds, the Britons' boasted chief.</q> <rj><qau>J.
Philips.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Figuratively: To bind or confine so as to prevent or
embarrass action; to impede; to cumber.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Shackled</qex> by her devotion to the king, she seldom could
pursue that object.</q> <rj><qau>Walpole.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To join by a link or chain, as railroad cars.</def>
<mark>[U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Shackle bar</b></col>, <cd>the coupling between a
locomotive and its tender.</cd> <mark>[U.S.]</mark> -- <col><b>Shackle
bolt</b></col>, <cd>a shackle.</cd> <rj><au>Sir W.
Scott.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shacklock</ent>⟦br⟧
